-- ============================================================
-- MORPHEUS8 — InMode
-- FDA-cleared: skin resurfacing, subdermal adipose tissue remodeling
-- Technology: Fractional RF microneedling, 24 gold-coated microneedle pins
-- Depths: 0.5mm–8mm (Morpheus8 Body: up to 8mm)
-- ============================================================

INSERT INTO agent_reference_docs (
  id, offering_id, category_id, lens, doc_type, audience, title, content_md,
  extends_doc_id, status, version
) VALUES (
  'b1e2a3f4-5c6d-7e8f-9a0b-1c2d3e4f5a6b',
  '84ac561e-1818-4ece-a8d7-1fb6c5ea80df',
  '836bcdf0-aa49-4dae-9ced-bd9c4a027299',
  'clinical', 'clinical_summary', 'provider',
  'Morpheus8 — Clinical Summary',
  E'## Product Identity\n\nMorpheus8 is a fractional radiofrequency (RF) microneedling device manufactured by InMode. It delivers bipolar RF energy through an array of 24 gold-coated microneedle electrodes that penetrate to controlled subdermal depths of 0.5–8 mm (standard face tip: up to 4 mm; Morpheus8 Body tip: up to 8 mm). The system is FDA-cleared for subdermal adipose tissue remodeling and skin resurfacing. [InMode 510k K192271]\n\n## Mechanism of Action\n\nMorpheus8 combines two mechanisms — mechanical micro-injury from needle penetration and thermal RF injury to subdermal collagen and adipose tissue. RF energy delivered at the needle tips creates focal thermal zones (coagulation columns) in the dermis and superficial fat. This dual insult triggers: (1) wound-healing cascade with dermal collagen and elastin remodeling, (2) subdermal adipose tissue remodeling via selective thermal constriction of fat septae. The fractional pattern spares inter-column tissue, enabling faster healing than fully ablative modalities. [InMode 510k; peer-reviewed: Weiss R. Lasers Surg Med 2022]\n\nKey parameter: RF energy is delivered in burst mode with tissue impedance feedback, concentrating energy at the needle tips (insulated shafts) to avoid superficial dermal heating — this reduces post-inflammatory hyperpigmentation (PIH) risk compared to uninsulated systems. [manufacturer IFU]\n\n## FDA-Cleared Indications\n\n- **Subdermal adipose tissue remodeling** in the face and body [InMode 510k K192271]\n- **Skin resurfacing (fractional)** — improvement of skin texture and tone [510k]\n\n**Off-label field uses (gateway posture — not FDA-cleared):** Acne scarring treatment, striae (stretch marks), laxity of neck, perioral area, periorbital area. These are field-standard applications with growing evidence but not enumerated in FDA clearance. [field practice; peer-reviewed: Oni G. Aesthet Surg J 2021]\n\n## Candidacy\n\n**Strong candidates:** Patients with skin laxity (mild to moderate), acne scarring, skin texture irregularities, and/or early jowling. Notably, Morpheus8 is effective across **Fitzpatrick skin types I–VI** due to its subdermal energy delivery — the insulated needle shafts limit epidermal thermal exposure, significantly reducing PIH risk for darker skin types compared to ablative and uninsulated RF systems. [peer-reviewed: Weiss R. Lasers Surg Med 2022; peer-reviewed: Oni G. Aesthet Surg J 2021]\n\n**Poor candidacy / contraindications (Safety Floor — FDA label, rank 1):**\n- Active skin infection, open wounds, or inflammatory skin disease at treatment site\n- Metal implants (pacemaker, defibrillator, implanted electronic devices) — RF energy contraindicated\n- Pregnancy\n- History of keloid scarring or hypertrophic scarring\n- Isotretinoin use within 6 months (impaired wound healing) [consensus]\n- Fitzpatrick types IV–VI: proceed with caution, lower settings, patch test; PIH risk exists even with insulated systems at aggressive parameters [field practice; peer-reviewed]\n\n## Safety Profile\n\n**Common adverse events:** Erythema and edema (expected, resolves 24–72 hours), pinpoint bleeding at needle entry sites, crusting/scabbing at microneedle puncture sites (resolves 5–7 days). [IFU; peer-reviewed]\n\n**Uncommon:** Post-inflammatory hyperpigmentation (PIH) — particularly in Fitzpatrick IV–VI if overtreated; thermal burns from poor electrical contact or overlapping passes; prolonged erythema >2 weeks; infection at entry sites.\n\n**Rare/serious:** Full-thickness burn with aggressive parameters or improper device use; fat atrophy with excessive subdermal energy (reported in body applications with very high energy). [peer-reviewed: Weiss R. Lasers Surg Med 2022]\n\n**Fitzpatrick-specific safety floor:** PIH is the primary safety concern for Fitzpatrick IV–VI. Mitigate with: lower energy settings, longer intervals between treatments, pre- and post-treatment topical hypopigmentation agents (hydroquinone, kojic acid), extended recovery monitoring. Never treat with aggressive parameters on darker skin types without clinical experience and patch test. [peer-reviewed; consensus]\n\n**PIH risk — mandatory disclosure:** Document Fitzpatrick type pre-treatment. For Fitzpatrick IV+: informed consent must address PIH risk explicitly. [field practice consensus]\n\n## Clinical Outcomes\n\nImprovement in skin laxity, texture, and acne scarring typically requires 1–3 treatment sessions spaced 4–6 weeks apart. Clinical response develops over 3–6 months post-treatment as collagen remodeling matures. Studies cite clinician-assessed improvement in laxity of 50–70% after 2–3 sessions; patient satisfaction rates above 80% in published series. [peer-reviewed: Mulholland RS. Clin Cosmet Investig Dermatol 2023; Lasers Surg Med 2022]\n\nGateway posture: "Treatment parameters, session number, and energy levels should be individualized — for exact protocols, refer to InMode IFU and clinical training materials [InMode IFU →]."',
  '77358d98-0c62-495a-90e2-487fe9f81a1d',
  'draft', 1
);

INSERT INTO agent_reference_docs (
  id, offering_id, category_id, lens, doc_type, audience, title, content_md,
  extends_doc_id, status, version
) VALUES (
  'c2d3e4f5-6a7b-8c9d-0e1f-2a3b4c5d6e7f',
  '84ac561e-1818-4ece-a8d7-1fb6c5ea80df',
  '836bcdf0-aa49-4dae-9ced-bd9c4a027299',
  'clinical', 'technique_guide', 'provider',
  'Morpheus8 — Technique Guide',
  E'## Treatment Depths and Tip Selection\n\n**Face tip (Morpheus8 standard):** Depths 0.5–4 mm. Common depth ranges by zone:\n- Periorbital area: 0.5–1.5 mm range (thin skin, avoid deep placement)\n- Mid-face/cheeks: 2–4 mm for dermis and superficial fat targeting\n- Neck and submental: 2–4 mm; lower settings given neck skin thinness\n- Acne scarring: 3–4 mm for subdermal remodeling + fibrolytic effect\n\n**Body tip (Morpheus8 Body):** Depths up to 8 mm. For body contouring applications (abdomen, flanks, thighs), deeper depths target fat septae remodeling. Significantly higher energy levels used for body vs. face — treat as a distinct protocol.\n\nGateway posture: Exact energy levels (mJ) and depth settings per anatomical zone are in InMode clinical training materials. Characterize parameters as "mid-range to high for laxity; lower range for surface texture refinement; lowest range for periorbital." [InMode IFU → for exact settings]\n\n## Pre-Treatment Assessment\n\n- Document Fitzpatrick skin type — determines settings and post-care protocol\n- Photograph treatment areas (standard views)\n- Topical anesthetic: EMLA or compounded lidocaine/tetracaine cream applied 30–60 minutes pre-treatment. Adequate anesthesia is essential — inadequately anesthetized patients will reflexively move during treatment, risking thermal injury.\n- Skin prep: clean, dry, free of all topical products\n- For Fitzpatrick IV+: discuss PIH risk, obtain written consent, consider pre-conditioning with 4% hydroquinone x 2–4 weeks [field practice consensus]\n\n## Treatment Technique Notes\n\n**Pass pattern:** Full-face protocol typically 2 passes per zone — first pass at deeper depth for subdermal remodeling, second at shallower depth for upper dermal tightening if desired. Single-depth single-pass for maintenance or sensitive zones.\n\n**Stamp vs. slide:** Morpheus8 uses a full stamp technique — device placed flat on skin, triggered, lifted, moved to adjacent zone. Do NOT drag the device while firing. Overlapping stamps by ~20–30% edges is described in manufacturer protocol; avoid full stamp overlap as this concentrates energy. [InMode IFU]\n\n**Combination with BoNT:** Botulinum toxin before or same session with energy devices is field-standard (BoNT first, or same visit for standard face devices). Filler sequencing: energy first, filler 2–4 weeks later — this avoids thermal exposure to recently placed filler and respects dermal architecture. [peer-reviewed: field practice consensus; sources differ on same-visit filler+device; gateway posture: see combination_sequencing literature]\n\n## Post-Treatment Care\n\n- Petrolatum/fragrance-free emollient immediately post-procedure and x 3–5 days\n- Sun avoidance strict for minimum 2 weeks; SPF 30+ indefinitely for treated areas\n- No exfoliants, retinoids, or AHAs x 7–14 days post-treatment\n- Fitzpatrick IV+: resume hydroquinone post-treatment x 2–4 weeks to manage PIH risk\n- Downtime: 24–72 hours of erythema, 3–7 days of microinflammation at needle sites\n\n## Combination Sequencing (Energy First)\n\nEnergy-based devices should generally be performed BEFORE filler injection in the same anatomical zone. Rationale: thermal injury to existing HA filler can cause accelerated degradation, gas formation, or aberrant inflammatory response. Industry consensus: if same-visit combination is chosen, inject filler AFTER energy treatment. For staged approach: minimum 2–4 weeks between energy and new filler placement in same zone. BoNT has no thermal concerns and is commonly same-visit. [field practice consensus; see DOSSIER_TEMPLATES combination_sequencing for full timing rules]',
  'bb289acc-bc72-4b27-855a-d41c9fb47056',
  'draft', 1
);

INSERT INTO agent_reference_docs (
  id, offering_id, category_id, lens, doc_type, audience, title, content_md,
  extends_doc_id, status, version
) VALUES (
  'd3e4f5a6-7b8c-9d0e-1f2a-3b4c5d6e7f8a',
  '84ac561e-1818-4ece-a8d7-1fb6c5ea80df',
  '836bcdf0-aa49-4dae-9ced-bd9c4a027299',
  'sales_education', 'patient_education', 'patient',
  'Morpheus8 — Patient Education',
  E'## What Morpheus8 Does\n\nMorpheus8 is a skin remodeling treatment that reaches beneath the surface to rebuild what makes skin look tight, smooth, and youthful — collagen and the deeper structural framework that holds it all up. It does this with a combination of tiny microneedles and radiofrequency energy that work together to trigger your skin''s own repair response.\n\nThink of it like this: your skin has layers. The surface layer shows the lines, texture, and laxity. But below it, there''s a scaffolding of collagen, elastin, and fat tissue that either supports the skin or lets it sag and thin. Most surface treatments — peels, topical serums, even standard microneedling — only reach the first layer. Morpheus8 goes deeper, into the tissue where structural change actually happens.\n\nThe result builds over 3–6 months as collagen matures. The change looks natural because it IS natural — your body''s own healing process, precisely guided.\n\n## What It Addresses\n\n- **Skin laxity:** Mild to moderate looseness in the face, jaw, neck, and body\n- **Acne scarring:** Subdermal remodeling breaks up the fibrous bands that tether acne scars down\n- **Skin texture:** Pore size, roughness, and surface unevenness\n- **Stretch marks:** Off-label, but one of the most compelling applications (subdermal collagen remodeling)\n- **Jowling and submental looseness:** Tightening effect on the lower face and under-chin area\n\n## Why Morpheus8 Specifically\n\nThe precision of the RF energy delivery is what sets Morpheus8 apart. The needle shafts are insulated — energy is concentrated at the tips in the dermis and below, not at the surface. This is significant for two reasons: first, it means the treatment works where structural change happens. Second, it means it is one of the very few RF microneedling devices that can safely be performed on **all skin tones**, including deeper complexions where surface heating from other devices causes pigmentation changes.\n\n## What to Expect\n\n**At the appointment:** A numbing cream is applied 30–60 minutes before treatment. Once numb, the treatment device is applied in a stamping pattern across the treatment areas. Most patients describe it as warmth with pressure — uncomfortable but manageable with adequate numbing.\n\n**After the treatment:** Skin will appear red and slightly swollen, similar to a moderate sunburn, for 24–72 hours. Small pinpoint marks at the needle sites resolve within 3–7 days. Most patients can return to normal activities (without makeup) within 24–48 hours.\n\n**When you see results:** Immediate mild tightening is common due to thermal collagen contraction. The primary result develops over 3–6 months as new collagen remodels. Most treatment plans include 1–3 sessions spaced 4–6 weeks apart.\n\n## Benefit Framing\n\nMorpheus8 is infrastructure investment for your skin — not a surface touch-up. Surface treatments improve what you see; Morpheus8 improves the structure that determines what you see. Patients who have tried peels, lasers, and light devices and hit a ceiling often find that Morpheus8 accomplishes what those surface approaches couldn''t, because the structural deficit isn''t in the epidermis — it''s below it.\n\nFor acne scars specifically, this is one of the most evidence-supported non-surgical interventions available for actual scar remodeling (not just camouflage).\n\n## Combination Therapy\n\nMorpheus8 addresses structure and texture; it does not address volume or movement. A complete rejuvenation plan often combines:\n- Morpheus8 for structure, texture, and laxity\n- Dermal filler (Voluma, Vollure) for volume restoration\n- Neurotoxin (Botox, Dysport) for dynamic lines that muscle relaxation corrects\n\nSequencing matters: energy treatments like Morpheus8 are done first, with filler placed afterward if combined in the same treatment cycle.\n\n## Maintenance\n\nCollagen production naturally slows with age — maintaining results typically means a single maintenance treatment every 1–2 years once the initial series achieves the structural improvement. Many patients find the maintenance dose is lower than the initial series. This is one of the investments in skin health that compounds: each treatment builds on prior remodeling.',
  'b12ad6fc-c35c-4dbc-a32c-21c714ee8ec8',
  'draft', 1
);

INSERT INTO agent_reference_docs (
  id, offering_id, category_id, lens, doc_type, audience, title, content_md,
  extends_doc_id, status, version
) VALUES (
  'e4f5a6b7-8c9d-0e1f-2a3b-4c5d6e7f8a9b',
  '84ac561e-1818-4ece-a8d7-1fb6c5ea80df',
  '836bcdf0-aa49-4dae-9ced-bd9c4a027299',
  'sales_education', 'faq', 'patient',
  'Morpheus8 — FAQ',
  E'## Common Questions\n\n**"Will it hurt?"**\nWith adequate numbing cream applied beforehand, most patients rate the treatment as tolerable. Inadequate numbing is the main cause of significant discomfort — your provider will ensure full topical anesthesia before starting.\n\n**"How much downtime?"**\nExpect 24–72 hours of redness and 3–7 days of minor skin texture changes at the needle entry sites. Most people are comfortable going out without makeup within 48 hours. Plan to avoid intense sun exposure for at least 2 weeks.\n\n**"Can I do this if I have a darker skin tone?"**\nYes — Morpheus8''s insulated needle design is specifically notable because it can be performed safely on all Fitzpatrick skin types, including deeper complexions. Many other RF and laser devices carry significant pigmentation risk for darker skin tones. Morpheus8 is one of the few devices with a strong safety record across the full skin tone spectrum. Your provider will adjust settings for your skin type.\n\n**"How many treatments do I need?"**\nMost laxity and texture concerns are addressed in 1–3 sessions spaced 4–6 weeks apart. Acne scarring typically requires more sessions than laxity. Your provider will recommend a series based on your goals and starting point.\n\n**"When will I see results?"**\nSome immediate tightening is visible within days due to thermal collagen contraction. The primary, lasting result develops over 3–6 months as new collagen matures. This is not a "one-week" treatment — it''s a structural remodeling process.\n\n**"Is it safe with filler?"**\nYes, but timing matters. If you have existing filler in the area, your provider will typically wait to do energy treatments, or sequence energy first and filler afterward. Filler and Morpheus8 are excellent complements in a complete treatment plan — just not layered on top of each other same-session without planning.\n\n## Objection Reframes\n\n**"I''m scared of the downtime."**\nThe Morpheus8 recovery is predictable and short. Two to three days of redness and 5–7 days of minor skin texture changes — most patients are comfortable with normal activities within 48 hours. The return on investment compared to surgical alternatives (weeks of recovery, scarring risk) is dramatically in Morpheus8''s favor.\n\n**"Why not just do a laser?"**\nLasers work at the surface and have significant PIH risk in darker skin tones and significant downtime in ablative formats. Morpheus8 works below the surface to address structural laxity — a concern that lasers cannot treat. For the concerns Morpheus8 addresses (laxity, scarring, subdermal remodeling), it is the right tool; for surface pigmentation, a different device may be more appropriate. Often both are used in a treatment plan.\n\n**"This feels like a lot of money for something I can''t see immediately."**\nMorpheus8''s value is in the structural result — which most patients say looks better at 6 months than at 6 days. The collagen you build doesn''t disappear overnight; you''re investing in structural tissue that compounds over months. Comparing it to surface treatments that need to be repeated every few weeks, the cost-per-lasting-result is typically more favorable.',
  'b12ad6fc-c35c-4dbc-a32c-21c714ee8ec8',
  'draft', 1
);

INSERT INTO agent_reference_docs (
  id, offering_id, category_id, lens, doc_type, audience, title, content_md,
  extends_doc_id, status, version
) VALUES (
  'f5a6b7c8-9d0e-1f2a-3b4c-5d6e7f8a9b0c',
  '84ac561e-1818-4ece-a8d7-1fb6c5ea80df',
  '836bcdf0-aa49-4dae-9ced-bd9c4a027299',
  'deep_product', 'deep_dive_playbook', 'provider',
  'Morpheus8 — Deep Dive Playbook',
  E'## Product Differentiation\n\nMorpheus8 differentiates within the RF microneedling category primarily on three axes:\n\n1. **Insulated needles with subdermal depth range (up to 8mm on body):** Unlike some RF microneedling systems using semi-insulated or uninsulated electrodes, Morpheus8''s full-shaft insulation concentrates energy at the needle tips. This enables deep subdermal adipose remodeling (the 8mm body tip is unique in the category) while minimizing epidermal thermal exposure.\n\n2. **Fitzpatrick safety across all types:** The insulated tip design substantially reduces PIH risk compared to fully ablative and uninsulated RF devices, supporting use in Fitzpatrick IV–VI patients where many competitors are cautious or contraindicated. This is a significant market differentiator — a meaningful portion of aesthetic patients have Fitzpatrick IV+ skin.\n\n3. **InMode platform integration:** Morpheus8 is part of the InMode platform (shared console with Votiva, BodyTite, FaceTite, etc.), enabling multi-indication coverage from a single capital equipment investment. This is a clinic-economics differentiator.\n\n**Within the InMode portfolio:** Morpheus8 is the transcutaneous (non-surgical) option. FaceTite is InMode''s minimally invasive RF lipolysis option (cannula-based, more aggressive laxity correction but surgical suite required). Morpheus8 and FaceTite are often positioned as two tiers of the same clinic''s laxity correction pathway.\n\n## Mechanism Detail\n\nBipolar RF at approximately 1 MHz delivered through 24-pin fractional array. The fractional heating pattern creates focal thermal coagulation zones (TCZ) at tip level. TCZ dimensions vary with energy (mJ) and duration settings. Between TCZs: untreated tissue corridors that enable rapid epithelial healing (fractional principle). Collagen synthesis response: type I and III collagen deposition in dermal and subdermal layers over 3–6 months post-treatment. Fat remodeling: thermal constriction of adipocyte lobules, fibroseptal contraction; mechanism less characterized than dermal collagen response. [peer-reviewed: Weiss R. Lasers Surg Med 2022; peer-reviewed: Mulholland RS. Clin Cosmet Investig Dermatol 2023]\n\n## Evidence Summary\n\n**Laxity (face/neck):** Multiple prospective studies show meaningful improvement in facial laxity scores after 2–3 sessions. Weiss et al. (Lasers Surg Med 2022) reported significant improvement in lower facial laxity. Oni et al. (Aesthet Surg J 2021) demonstrated neck and submental tightening outcomes. Evidence level: moderate (prospective case series, no large RCTs).\n\n**Acne scarring:** Growing body of evidence for fractional RF in atrophic acne scarring. Multiple published case series show significant improvement in scar severity scores; mechanism of subdermal fibrolysis is well-characterized. Evidence level: moderate.\n\n**Fitzpatrick safety:** Published series including Fitzpatrick IV–VI report low PIH rates with standard protocol (insulated tips + lower initial settings + sun avoidance protocol). [Lasers Surg Med; JCAD series]\n\n## Comparison Anchors\n\n| Feature | Morpheus8 | Standard RF Microneedling | Ablative CO2 Laser |\n|---------|-----------|--------------------------|-------------------|\n| Depth | 0.5–8mm (body) | 0.5–3.5mm typical | Surface–0.5mm |\n| PIH Risk (Fitz IV+) | Low (insulated) | Moderate | High |\n| Downtime | 3–7 days | 2–5 days | 7–14 days |\n| Fat remodeling | Yes (subdermal) | Minimal | No |\n| Recovery type | Microinflammation | Microinflammation | Weeping/crusting |\n\nGateway posture: Comparison data are from published literature and manufacturer materials; individual outcomes vary. Provider training and technique drive significant outcome variance.',
  '42abdc4c-dfeb-4ffa-8ed4-d8b11eb39d23',
  'draft', 1
);
